<DOC><DOCNO> AP890906-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1052EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Japan-TaxEvasion     09-06 0186</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Japan-Tax Evasion,0194</SECOND><HEAD>All But a Few People Investigated Found Evading Taxes</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   All but a few, or 98.5 percent of 3,628 inheritorsof assets, investigated by tax officials in the Tokyo area this yearwere found to be evading inheritance taxes, the Tokyo Regional TaxAdministration Bureau said Wednesday.   The bureau said it uncovered an all-time high of 150 billion yen,or about $1.02 billion, worth of unreported assets subject toinheritance taxes.   Accordingly, the taxes on those assets, combined with punitivetaxes, amounted to 53.4 billion yen, it said.   The bureau said 18,600 of 132,000 people who died in Tokyo andthe three adjacent cities of Chiba, Kanagawa and Yamanashi in 1988left behind assets subject to taxation.   Of the total, 3,628 cases were considered questionable, and thebureau conducted follow-up checks.   About 70 percent of the unreported assets were in the form ofstocks, golf club memberships, cash and savings. Golf clubmemberships are tradeable assets similar to stocks in Japan.   The bureau said one company executive topped the list for evadingtaxes totaling 118 million yen, or about $805,500.</TEXT></DOC>